s also looks at the intersection of individual life stories with the law, and considers the creation of an introspective project that culminates in psychoanalysis. Elegant and provocative, Enigmas of Identity offers new insights into the questions and clues about who we think we are.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aGroup identity. 0aPSYCHOLOGYvPersonality. 0aSOCIAL SCIENCEvDiscrimination &ampxRace Relations. 0aSOCIAL SCIENCEvMinority Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aBeethoven.  aEnlightenment.  aJean-Jacques Rousseau.  aMarcel Proust.  aMatisse.  aRenaissance.  aSigmund Freud.  aStendhal.  aautoeroticism.  acities.  acrime.  aculture.  aderealization.  adisciplined reproduction.  adisguise.  adouble agent.  aegotism.  afingerprinting.  afingerprints.  aidentificatory paradigm.  aidentity paradigm.  aidentity.  aimpostor.  aimposture.  aindividual identity.  aindividualism.  aintrospection.  ainviolate personality.  alate style.  alife stories.  amasturbation.  amisprision.  amodern culture.  amodern identity.  amodern nation-state.  amodern societies.  amodernity.  anarcissism.  anascent capitalism.  anecessity.  apersonal identity.  aprivacy.  aprivate identity.  aproteanism.  apsychoanalysis.  aretrospective narrator.  asearches.  aseizures.  aself dissolution.  aself dramatization.  aself estrangement.  aself-dissolution.  aself-love.  aself-obsession.  aself-reflexiveness.  aself-reinvention.  aself.  aselfhood.  asexuality.  asolipsism.  aspy.  aurbanism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400839698zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40